        <div id="post-content" class="col-md-offset-1 col-md-7">
          <h1>Random Walks</h1>
          <h2 id="introduction">Introduction</h2>
<p>The <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_walk_hypothesis">random walk hypothesis</a> states that stock market prices evolve according to a stochastic process, preventing the prediction of future stock market movements. The concept follows from the weak version of the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Efficient-market_hypothesis">efficient-market hypothesis</a>, which asserts that future stock market movements are not correlated with past movements. In other words, the movement of share prices on one day does not affect the movement of share prices on subsequent days.</p>

<p>Some economic research has countered this theory, showing the stock market to be predictive to some degree.  In this study, we will test the hypothesis by examining the distribution of winning and losing streaks in the stock market.</p>

<p>By writing custom metrics in <a href="https://docs.palantir.com/pflc/the-hedgehog-language.html">Hedgehog</a> (the Palantir Finance programming language), we can count the frequencies of streaks of every length in the major US indices (the DJIA, S&amp;P 500, and NASDAQ). Based on the overall fraction of trading days with positive closings, we can also calculate the expected distribution of winning and non-winning streaks in the indices and compare their relative frequencies.</p>

<p>(For our purposes, a “winning streak” will be considered to be one or more consecutive trading days of positive gains. Similarly, a “non-winning streak” indicates one or more consecutive trading days of zero or negative change.)</p>

<h2 id="data-amp-observations">Data &amp; Observations</h2>

<p>The following screenshot from the Calculator app shows the computation of data on winning streaks in the major US indices (click images to enlarge):</p>

<p><img title="Calculator" src="/wp-assets/wp-content/static/pf-analysis-blog/2011/01/calculator-small.jpg" /><br />
<em>Figure 1: Calculation of actual win streak distributions in the major US indices (lines 1, 4, 7), their expected distributions (lines 2, 5, 8), and the ratios of the two (lines 3, 6, 9)</em></p>

<p>The full results for the NASDAQ are summarized in the table below:</p>

