<td width="66" valign="bottom">0.000</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td width="97" valign="top">19</td>
<td width="90" valign="bottom">1</td>
<td width="72" valign="bottom">0.0</td>
<td width="59" valign="bottom">35.00</td>
<td width="73" valign="bottom">0</td>
<td width="72" valign="bottom">0.0</td>
<td width="66" valign="bottom">0.000</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td width="97" valign="top">20+</td>
<td width="90" valign="bottom">0</td>
<td width="72" valign="bottom">0.0</td>
<td width="59" valign="bottom">0.000</td>
<td width="73" valign="bottom">0</td>
<td width="72" valign="bottom">0.0</td>
<td width="66" valign="bottom">0.000</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p>Although intuition may suggest fewer long streaks relative to a random distribution (due to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean_reversion_(finance)">mean reversion</a>), in fact it is streaks of one and two days which are under-represented. As longer streaks are correspondingly more frequent, this indicates a strategy of buying long an index at the start of a win streak (which is unlikely to be confined to a day or two) may be profitable. Similar logic suggests selling short an index at the start of a non-winning streak. In Palantir, we can easily test these hypotheses.</p>

<h2 id="strategy-implementation-and-results">Strategy: Implementation and Results</h2>

<p>Using the <a href="https://docs.palantir.com/pflc/date-set.html">Date Set</a> feature, we will begin by isolating the first and second days of winning and non-winning streaks. In the screenshot below, we have isolated the days of one-day winning streaks by selecting the days of positive closings that were preceded by days of negative or no change:</p>

<p><img title="Date Set" src="/wp-assets/wp-content/static/pf-analysis-blog/2011/01/dateset-small.jpg" /><br />
<em>Figure 2: Start days of NASDAQ winning streaks</em></p>

<p>Next, using our custom date sets, we can backtest with the <a href="https://docs.palantir.com/pflc/strategy.html">Strategy</a> application. We will hold long the NASDAQ index at close on the first day of a winning streak, exiting our position at close of the end or third day of the streak. At close on the first day of a losing streak, we will sell short the index, exiting our position at close of the end or third day of the streak. In the screenshot below, we can see both the code (left panel) and the results (lower right):</p>

<p><img title="Streak Strategy" src="/wp-assets/wp-content/static/pf-analysis-blog/2011/01/strategy-1-small.jpg" /><br />
<em>Figure 3: The streak strategy, backtested on the last 39 years of the NASDAQ index</em></p>

<p>We can also look at the result of a simple buy-and-hold strategy of the index over the same time period:</p>

<p><img title="Buying and Holding" src="/wp-assets/wp-content/static/pf-analysis-blog/2011/01/strategy-2-small.jpg" /><br />
<em>Figure 4: The result of buying and holding the NASDAQ index over the same time period as in Figure 3</em></p>

<p>The streak strategy is quite impressive in comparison to the buy-and-hold strategy, with an annualized return over 13 percentage points higher, and a total return nearly 100x higher over the 39-year period.</p>

<p>Let’s take a closer look at the results. Using the <a href="https://docs.palantir.com/pflc/chart.html">Chart</a> tool, we can compare the performance of our streak strategy to the buy-and-hold strategy over time:</p>

<p><img title="Comparison" src="/wp-assets/wp-content/static/pf-analysis-blog/2011/01/chart-1-small.jpg" /><br />
<em>Figure 5: Comparing the results of the streak strategy (blue lines) and holding strategy (green lines)</em></p>

<p>The top chart shows the growth of an initial $1,000,000 investment in the NASDAQ under both the streak strategy (blue line) and the buy-and-hold strategy (green line).  The middle chart plots the yearly percentage change of both approaches, while the bottom chart plots the spread of the percentage changes (positive values indicating the streak strategy outperformed the buy-and-hold, negative values the reverse).</p>

<p>While the overall strategy return is very impressive, comparing the results over time shows that the recent performance has been less than stellar.  Through 1997, the streak strategy out-performed holding the index by an average of 22 percentage points per year.  However, since 2003, it has underperformed the index by an average of 18 percentage points per year.  This is further illustrated in the chart below, where the returns have been normalized to the start of 2003.  The NASDAQ has approximately doubled over the time period, while the streak strategy lost nearly half of its starting value.</p>

<p><img title="NASDAQ Streak" src="/wp-assets/wp-content/static/pf-analysis-blog/2011/01/chart-2-small.jpg" /><br />
<em>Figure 6: Returns of the NASDAQ streak and buy-and-hold strategies since 2003</em></p>

<h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>

<p>We have compared the past movements of stock indices to random walks, and shown how deviations from random behavior may be capitalized on for large gains. From here, we could build more elaborate strategies that incorporate trades during longer streaks. The long and short components of the strategy, as well as the one and two day streak actions can also be isolated to determine their individual contributions. The effectiveness of the streak strategy on international indices (the Nikkei, FTSE, etc.) can also be easily investigated.</p>

